<TEXT>
a young hijacker surrendered to police 
sunday after forcing a soviet airliner on a domestic flight to land 
in finland authorities said the 72 passengers and six crew 
members were released unharmed 
police commissioner pentti luntiala speaking to reporters 
quoted the 21yearold man as saying he wanted to seek political 
asylum and go to the united states 
it was the second soviet hijack incident in finland in a week 
and the third in a scandinavian country in two weeks there was 
also a fourth incident involving the commandeering of a soviet 
aircraft with no passengers aboard 
the hijacker commandeered the twinengine tupolev 134 bound 
from the estonian capital of tallinn to lvov in the ukraine by 
saying he carried a bomb in his luggage an official at helsinkis 
international airport said 
the official terminal duty officer pirjo lahteela said police 
were searching the plane for explosives and the hijacker was being 
interrogated 
the aeroflot airliner landed at helsinkis international airport 
at about 830 am 130 am edt time authorities said 
last tuesday a 20yearold hijacker forced a soviet airliner 
with 60 people aboard to land in finland and asked for political 
asylum no one was injured in that incident moscow asked helsinki 
to extradite the hijacker identified as oleg kozlov 
a day earlier a 29yearold pilot valeri yuricevic 
commandeered a 12seat antonov2 aircraft in izmail near the 
ukrainian port of odessa and flew to turkey where he asked for 
asylum there was no one else on board 
on june 9 dimitry semionov a 17yearold soviet youth used a 
fake hand grenade to hijack a plane carrying 121 passengers during 
a flight from minsk to murmansk that plane was forced to fly to 
stockholm where semionov surrendered 
the youth said later through a lawyer he had acted on impulse 
after a family quarrel and wanted to go to a free country 
semionov was arraigned in a stockholm court and could face up to 
four years in prison depending on the results of psychiatric tests 
