<TEXT>
high wind and heavy rain from typhoon percy 
battered palau on sunday night leaving a child dead and knocking 
out utility service a newspaper reported 
a young boy died saturday night when he was swept by rain into 
mangrove trees near his home in the cluster of islands that 
comprise palau the pacific daily news said 
the storm passed 90 miles north of palau which is 800 miles 
south of agana said navy ensign richard jeffries of the joint 
typhoon warning center 
the typhoon moved westnorthwest at 16 mph on a path that could 
take it between taiwan and the philippines in four or five days 
jeffries said 
wind gusts of up to 103 mph blew off tin roofs of many buildings 
and knocked radio and television stations off the air the pacific 
daily news said 
airline flights into the republic were canceled the newspaper 
said 
earlier sunday the typhoons winds battered yap island in the 
neighboring federated states of micronesia collapsing about 30 
houses and damaging banana and coconut plantations police said 
there were no reports of injuries on yap and the winds and 
accompanying heavy rains posed no problems for the islands 
electric and water systems officer kenneth chugrad said 
