<TEXT>
the strongest aftershock in three days hit a 
quakedevastated northern province sunday and a moderate 
earthquake was reported in southern iran 
the stench of decomposing bodies hung over gilan and zanjan 
provinces the two hardest hit in thursdays earthquake as 
rescuers aided by police dogs pulled corpses from the rubble and 
quickly buried them in mass graves to stem the outbreak of disease 
a senior un relief official said sunday in geneva that 
authorities fear the death toll may reach 50000 some official 
iranian reports have set the toll at 40000 
tehran times the nations leading englishlanguage newspaper 
quoted an unnamed official as saying 50000 people died and 200000 
were injured in the quake he said even that was a conservative 
estimate because the figures are quoted taking account only of 
those who have been registered officially as dead or wounded 
there are areas where bodies were buried without counting 
them he was quoted as saying 
tehran universitys geophysics center reported 60 aftershocks in 
the northern provinces the strongest of which jolted rasht 
capital of gilan province at 116 pm 546 am edt sunday it 
measured 57 on the richter scale 
the aftershock was the worst since several thursday shortly 
following the quake irna said details of casualties or damage from 
the aftershock were not immediately available but the 
rashtrudbar road which had just been reopened was once again 
blocked by the latest tremor which caused a mountain slide 
rasht is 35 miles north of rudbar which is on the border 
between gilan and zanjan provinces 
the geophysics center also reported a moderate earthquake 
measuring 49 on the richter scale in southern iran at 839 am 
109 pm it caused no casualties or damage no further details 
were available 
the center in a statement carried by the official islamic 
republic news agency said 360 tremors have struck northern iran 
since the quake 
the aftershocks have caused massive landslides blocking many 
roads leading to demolished villages on the northern edge of gilan 
on the caspian sea 
irna monitored in cyprus said more than 72 hours after the 
horrifying earthquake many villages in the mountainous region 
which have been leveled remain inaccessible 
the agency quoted a survivor from abbor village in zanjan as 
saying so many bodies have perished under the rubble they have 
not been retrieved or buried 
the whole area is stinking because of the decaying corpses 
which make rescue operations even more difficult the survivor 
identified as ahmad ali was quoted as saying 
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an 
earthquake as measured by the ground motion recorded on a 
seismograph 
