<DOCNO> AP900624-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
public housing tenants known to deal drugs 
will be kicked out of their apartments during nationwide raids set 
to begin this week even if they havent been convicted of a crime 
officials say 
federal marshals are scheduled monday to begin raiding 
apartments in housing projects located in as many as 22 cities 
where the holder of the lease is a known drug dealer and could be 
prosecuted for two felonies officials said 
the tenant and his or her family may be kicked out of the 
apartment even if the person has not yet been convicted of a drug 
crime under the program first announced last month by housing 
secretary jack kemp officials said 
the government calls the actions leasehold forfeitures not 
evictions the plan already has stirred up a legal challenge in one 
city 
the forfeiture of publichousing leases by known drug dealers is 
specifically authorized by assetforfeiture provisions of the 1988 
antidrug abuse act government officials say the same provisions 
enable federal prosecutors to seize boats cars and cash of drug 
dealers awaiting trial 
in this case the lease is the asset to be seized 
the raids are scheduled to be conducted in cities where 
authorities have identified drug dealing in housing projects as a 
significant problem 
the targeted housing projects are in some of the nations 
largest cities new york los angeles chicago as well as 
smaller municipalities such as chandler ariz tacoma wash and 
frederick md according to a list obtained by the associated 
press 
bob nipp a spokesman for the department of housing and urban 
development declined to comment on the planned raids when kemp 
first announced the plan he declined to identify the cities where 
housing projects would be raided 
civil libertarians have criticized the planned raids saying 
they will violate the principle that a person is innocent of 
criminal wrongdoing until proven guilty 
legal aid lawyers in richmond va one of the targeted cities 
last week obtained a temporary restraining order from a federal 
judge barring the government from removing tenants without giving 
them advance notice and an opportunity to be heard 
the order by us district judge richard l williams in effect 
affords tenants some of the due process of eviction proceedings it 
only applies to the richmond area but legal aid lawyers are 
expected to seek similar court rulings in other cities 
under guidelines adopted by the department of housing and urban 
development and the justice department only apartments that are 
notorious and open sites of drug distribution and leased by known 
drug dealers will be raided officials said 
the guidelines also state that authorities should have proof 
beyond a reasonable doubt that the leaseholder committed at least 
two felony drug crimes and will face prosecution said the 
officials who spoke on condition of anonymity 
it was not known if authorities also planned to serve search 
warrants to seek possible evidence of drug activity 
the plan calls for using local social service agencies to 
relocate children and elderly people who will be displaced from 
their homes by the raids officials said 
public housing projects in the following cities also have been 
targeted washington atlanta dallas baltimore hartford conn 
newark nj indianapolis flint mich charleston sc macon 
ga el paso texas kansas city omaha portland ore and st 
louis mo 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

