<DOCNO> AP900624-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when last seen the sr71 blackbird spy plane 
was slicing through a dreary march sky for a recordsetting final 
coasttocoast flight that touched off regrets and doubts over its 
retirement 
the air force and congress had decided several months earlier 
that the reconnaissance aircraft which provided unsurpassed 
snooping during the cold war had become too costly and that 
satellites could do the job easily 
shortly after its 68minute 17second trip from los angeles to 
washington blackbird no 17972 was shipped off to the smithsonian 
institution 
but the blackbird wasnt quite dead yet 
tucked away in the report accompanying a 4 billion spending 
bill that president bush signed last month was a provision telling 
the pentagon to maintain at least six of the spy planes for use in 
the event of a national crisis 
the above outlined program should not be considered a charter 
for reestablishment of sr71 flight operations which were 
terminated as a part of the fiscal 1990 budget deliberations the 
report said 
rather the intent of the lawmakers action was to ensure that 
the national aeronautics and space administration which will 
receive three of the planes has enough funds to conduct 
aeronautics research and that the air force could begin flight 
operations within 90 days of an emergency 
the report even designated the aircraft by tail numbers for the 
contingency program 
although the report provision is nonbinding pentagon refusal 
to adhere to the language would be too costly in the tenuous 
relationship between congress and the bush administration 
thus behindthescenes negotiations have been going on between 
the air force and several congressional committees over the report 
language and the cost to maintain the black daggershaped planes 
is a major issue 
lawmakers and congressional sources who requested anonymity 
said air force gen michael j dugan told members of congress that 
the cost of maintenance would total 30 million 
dugan is commander of the air force in europe and president 
bushs nominee for chief of staff a selection the senate armed 
services committee approved last week 
the report said the air force should use 6 million of money it 
already has for upkeep of the aircraft 
shortly before pentagon and congressional negotiators sought a 
common ground on the issue defense secretary dick cheney staked 
out his position in testimony before the senate appropriations 
defense subcommittee 
we can park them cheney told the panel earlier this month 
we cant bring them back within 90 days without going back and 
spending a lot of money to reconstitute at least a portion of 
manpower and maintenance and so forth and recertify pilots 
dugan in his senate confirmation hearing complained of the 
conflicting guidance from the congress on the issue 
the resources to get the five or six airplanes operational 
within a 90day period those resources are considerably more than 
made available dugan told the armed services panel 
rep joseph mcdade of pennsylvania ranking republican on the 
house appropriations subcommittee on defense said lawmakers did 
not believe the report provision was an unreasonable 
disposition for the spy plane 
the blackbird regularly flew missions over heavily defended 
north vietnam and provided intelligence in many other regions 
including the middle east china and the persian gulf 
the plane can outrun the fastest fighters and has never been 
shot down built to withstand temperatures of more than 800 degrees 
fahrenheit its skin is a titanium alloy instead of the aluminum 
used on most airplanes it can sustain a speed of mach 3 or three 
times the speed of sound but its maximum speed is classified 
mcdade noted that cheney during his tenure as a wyoming 
congressman on the house intelligence committee had opposed the 
blackbird 
cheney always felt the system was not a costeffective system 
he didnt think it justified the expenditures mcdade said in an 
interview last week 
congressional sources said the provision in the spending bill 
report was perceived by the armed services intelligence and 
appropriations committees as the best opportunity to resolve the 
issue and negotiations were going well 
if they fail however the question of the highflying blackbird 
is certain to surface in next years defense bills which congress 
will begin crafting later this summer 
theyre not going to recreate the sr71 but its not going 
away lock stock and barrel one congressional source said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

