<TEXT>
a young soviet hijacker claiming to 
have a bomb in his briefcase forced a soviet domestic airliner to 
land in finland on sunday then surrendered to police airport 
officials said 
the 71 other passengers and six crew were released unharmed and 
police found no explosives or arms aboard the airliner said erkki 
lepola head of air traffic controllers at helsinki airport 
it was the second hijacking of a soviet aircraft to finland in 
less than a week and the third to scandinavia in two weeks 
finnish authorities said they were concerned and would raise the 
issue with moscow 
the plane a tupolev 134 was on an internal flight from 
tallinn estonias capital to lvov in the ukraine 
the hijacker a 21yearold russian asked for political asylum 
in finland he refused to explain his motive before speaking to a 
lawyer 
police earlier said the hijacker had asked for political asylum 
in the united states 
a soviet civil aviation official in moscow identified the 
hijacker as m varfolomeyev finnish authorities refused to confirm 
his identity because of his asylum request soviet authorities have 
asked for his extradition 
witnesses said varfolomeyev took control of the plane five 
minutes after takeoff from tallinn and demanded that the crew 
divert the flight to stockholm sweden 
about five minutes after takeoff he went to the toilet with 
his briefcase then to an air hostess so i thought he was sick 
said vladimir vager a passenger who sat next to the hijacker 
when he came back to his seat he said to us all of you 
remain seated and obey me and he said he had a bomb in his 
briefcase vager told the associated press he said everyone on 
the plane remained calm 
after conferring with the rest of the crew the copilot told the 
hijacker the plane did not have enough fuel to reach stockholm 
varfolomeyev agreed to fly to helsinki where the plane landed 
sunday morning 
when we had landed police came on board with an interpreter 
and took the hijacker off the plane said vager 
the briefcase and hand luggage were put on the runway and 
examined with the help of dogs while the plane was searched for 
explosives none was found 
the aircraft left later for the soviet union tv news in 
helsinki reported 
on tuesday another soviet airplane was diverted to helsinki but 
had difficulty communicating with the finns tass the soviet news 
agency reported that the crew needed the help of the pilot of a 
west german light plane bound for helsinki 
the 20yearold hijacker of tuesdays flight who was identified 
as oleg kozlov is in police custody in helsinki 
kozlov also asked for political asylum after surrendering to 
finnish authorities he told police his intention was to reach the 
united states 
finland which has traditionally close ties with the soviet 
union has granted asylum to a soviet citizen only once before 
since world war ii in 1973 officials refuse to discuss that case 
on june 9 17yearold dimitry semionov forced a domestic soviet 
plane to land in sweden by threatening the pilot with a dummy hand 
grenade all 114 passengers and seven crew were unharmed and 
semionov surrendered 
semionov has been arraigned in court but has not asked for 
political asylum he said he wanted to leave his home in 
byelorussia after a quarrel with his father 
