<TEXT>
molly cooke happened to be a physician at 
san francisco general hospital in the eye of the aids storm when 
the epidemic blew in a decade ago and if she had it to do over 
again she would 
but some of the 1045 residents she and other researchers 
interviewed at 41 internal medicine programs across the nation are 
so fearful of contracting the deadly virus and so prejudiced 
against the groups of people primarily infected that they want 
nothing to do with aids treatment 
the residents intention to care for hivinfected people was 
low by all measures cooke said some residents would not treat 
to save a life in the face of any seroconversion risk and only 17 
percent of the residents indicated a strong intent to accommodate 
hivinfected people in practice 
distaste for the groups of people disproportionately affected by 
the disease was the one factor that distinguished doctors who had 
no plans to treat hiv and those who did cooke said on saturday in 
her report to the sixth international conference on aids 
some 65 percent of those surveyed agreed with the statement 
most iv drugusing patients with aids have brought the disease on 
themselves fortysix percent agreed with the same statement when 
the phrase gay patients was substituted and 35 percent agreed 
when minority patients filled the blank 
eighty percent of the residents thought that treating aids was 
difficult and more than half were insecure about their ability to 
offer proper social support onequarter believed caring for aids 
patients was unpleasant because they always die 
whats happening is everybodys scared and there are some 
people who have say a high sense of professional duty they say 
i may be scared but this is what doctors do cooke said 
other people have a low sense of professional duty or are very 
prejudiced they say these people are not worth me dealing with 
all this fear about so im going to take myself somewhere else 
where i dont have to feel this anxiety all the time 
cooke said more than half the residents believed that hiv will 
prove to be transmissible in ways now believed to be safe and 
twothirds said they were afraid of being infected on the job 
thirtysix percent said their practices wouldnt be set up to 
accommodate hivinfected patients 
theres a myth that i ran into all the time in the mid80s 
when i would go out and talk to doctors in other hospitals about 
what we were doing she said and what people would say was 
you can do that because somehow at san francisco general youre 
different but it scares us too much 
for years she would reply you shouldnt be scared theres 
nothing to be scared about she finally decided that wasnt true 
i learned to say its very scary cooke said the point 
is not whether youre scared the point is what you do next 
cooke said the researchers plan to follow the residents and find 
out what they actually do when their training is done 
people who are hivinfected already have to deal with a number 
of obstacles to getting care cooke said theres 
discrimination the treatments are expensive the hivinfected 
patients in the second wave have enormous social problems in their 
lives that are impediments to care 
and i think the unwillingness of physicians may be added to 
that list 
