<TEXT>
for thousands of alaskans venturing into 
the wild to hunt fish and gather plants for food is as much a 
routine part of their daily lives as a trip to the supermarket is 
for most americans 
the right to live off natures bounty in this wildliferich 
state is at the center of a dispute that has the federal government 
poised for an unprecedented takeover of game management in most of 
alaska next week 
the takeover is the result of an alaska supreme court ruling 
that put state and federal laws governing subsistence hunting and 
fishing at odds 
on monday the alaska legislature convenes in special session to 
consider an amendment to the state constitution that would 
guarantee that rural alaskans continue to have first crack at fish 
and game for subsistence uses 
gov steve cowper says the amendment is the only way to avert a 
permanent federal takeover of game management on the twothirds of 
alaska that is federally owned 
in alaska subsistence hunting fishing and gathering is a 
traditional way of life central to the states indian aleut and 
eskimo cultures 
it is the means for them to provide food to feed their 
extended families and their communities said julie kitka 
president of the alaska federation of natives its the core of 
their existence 
but indians aleuts and eskimos comprise fewer than half of the 
estimated 110000 alaskans who take part in subsistence activities 
in much of alaska the absence of stores and roads to the cities 
makes subsistence hunting and fishing a necessity 
subsistence is defined and protected for alaskans in state and 
federal law in fact alaska is the only state that gives 
subsistence use of fish and game the highest priority when 
decisions are made about catch limits and seasons sport and 
commercial hunters and fishermen take a back seat 
subsistence and the way its regulated has been an issue in 
alaska since statehood 31 year ago the states first subsistence 
law was enacted in 1978 and there have been repeated legal 
challenges 
public support for subsistence rights has remained strong 
however an initiative to repeal the subsistence law failed by a 
wide margin in 1982 and a statewide poll in march showed solid 
support for the constitutional amendment 
the latest dispute began in december when the alaska supreme 
court ruled that part of a state law that limits subsistence 
activities to rural residents unconstitutionally discriminates 
against urbanites 
but a federal law the alaska national interest lands 
conservation act of 1980 requires a rural preference as a result 
five federal land agencies plan to assume game management of 
alaskas federal land about 180 million acres on july 1 to 
protect the rural subsistence right 
the takeover which doesnt affect management of the states 
fisheries is expected to lead to considerable confusion among 
hunters as they are faced with differing regulations on alaskas 
patchwork of public lands 
federal land mangers said they were taking over control of the 
wildlife because of the federal requirement for the rural 
preference but they said they were doing so only reluctantly 
because of the complexity of setting hunting seasons bag limits 
and the like over such a wide area 
its the worst jigsaw you can imagine said bruce batten a 
spokesman for the federal fish and wildlife service 
the court had stayed the rulings effective date until july 1 to 
give the state time to find an alternative solution but thus far 
lawmakers have failed to pass a constitutional amendment bill 
some advocate a permit system that would provide subsistence 
rights only to those who meet certain requirements based on 
traditional use and need regardless of where they live 
it seems to me you lose some people out in the bush and gain 
some people in the urban areas said rep robin taylor 
rwrangell and house minority leader i think it would be kind of 
wash 
a group of environmental and sportsmens groups and individual 
plaintiffs in the lawsuit that led to the supreme court ruling 
filed another lawsuit friday seeking to overturn the federal rural 
preference 
if an amendment is not put to voters in november it would be 
two years before the legislature could get another amendment on the 
ballot 
cowper fears that if federal game management is allowed to 
continue past this year it could expand and become more 
restrictive 
by the weekend legislative support for a constitutional 
amendment appeared to be increasing cowper a democrat got help 
from the states allrepublican congressional delegation when it 
endorsed his plan friday 
us sen ted stevens was scheduled to address a joint session 
of the legislature on monday and urge passage of the amendment 
</TEXT>
