the senate when he and scherer each placed a condominium into their 
joint venture and named it the 703603 association not using the 
senators name durenberger rented the condominium from the 
association 
bennett further said that the 1987 sale to the firm headed by 
durenbergers excampaign manager paul overgaard was engineered 
solely to continue the reimbursements the transaction documents 
show was an oral agreement and final papers were not signed until 
october 1989 after overgaard threatened to cancel the deal due to 
the delays 
durenberger said he bought the condominium in 1979 but when it 
became too costly in 1983 he placed it in the partnership with 
scherer a former minnesota state legislator and a businessman he 
said he made the deal with overgaard after scherer said he was 
backing out of the partnership 
durenberger said he made the 1983 ownership change because a 
political adviser told him he could qualify for senate 
reimbursements by renting the condominium or staying in a hotel 
but not if he owned the residence 
in fact senate rules are unclear on how ownership affects 
reimbursements when a senator stays in his home state 
in an interview with ethics committee lawyers in april 1989 
mahoney stated our advice was we cant confirm nor could we 
deny that durenberger was correct in his interpretation that the 
rules allowed the reimbursements we simply couldnt find any 
support for it 
in his defense durenberger pointed to a legal opinion he was 
given june 28 1983 by another lawyer randall e johnson 
johnsons sworn statement to the committee on june 7 said he 
advised durenberger seven years ago that under senate rules i 
believed he could claim reimbursement for official business stays 
at the condominium that he rented from the partnership 
