they listened and took notes said terry dosh one of five 
former priests at the meeting none of us got our hopes up that 
anything could happen immediately were realists 
the four bishops including pierre dumaine of the san jose 
diocese agreed to take the request to their national committees 
for further discussion at least one bishop appeared to support the 
former priests cause 
within the framework of the discipline of the church which 
has served the church well over the centuries these men should be 
encouraged to put their life experience at the churchs service 
bishop donald wuerl of pittsburgh said in a prepared statement 
the former priests are members of a minneapolisbased group 
called corpus or the corps of reserve priests united for service 
which held an annual meeting over the weekend at san jose state 
university 
the group claims about 10000 members about half of them 
priests who married and are no longer allowed to serve 
the meeting with the bishops was the first since the 1978 
election of pope john paul ii who opposes letting married priests 
or women celebrate mass or perform other priestly duties 
corpus president anthony padovano said the group tried before to 
meet with bishops without success corpus hopes the church will 
reconsider the ban on married priests this fall at an international 
meeting of bishops in rome 
despite its insistence on a celibate clergy the church in 
recent years has allowed married episcopal priests to convert to 
roman catholicism remain married and celebrate mass hear 
confessions and perform other priestly duties 
thats a double standard said guy murning who was ordained 
as a roman catholic priest in 1970 but left eight years later to 
