japan surpassed the united states to become the 
biggest donor of government aid to the third world in 1989 the 
organization for economic cooperation and development said 
the achievement could soften criticism that japan with its 
immense financial strength has not done its share to help 
developing countries 
japans total aid effort in 1989 was 9 billion compared with 
77 billion for the us the parisbased organization of 
industrial democracies said in a report 
the us figure represented a decline of 27 percent from 1988 
after adjusting for inflation the decline meant that us aid as a 
share of gross national product declined from 021 percent in 1988 
to 015 percent last year the worst performance among the oecds 
main aid donor countries 
joseph wheeler chairman of the oecds development assistance 
committee told a news conference sunday the us aid figure for 
1989 understates the us effort in the same way the 1988 total 
overstated aid disbursements 
if us contributions to multilateral aid institutions were 
spread evenly over the two years instead of bunched more heavily in 
1988 wheeler said the level each year would have been 89 
billion equivalent to 018 percent of gnp in 1988 and 017 percent 
in 1989 
but the oecd said us bilateral aid to the third world has 
fallen steadily in recent years 
